  planner_response {
    modified_response: "I have resolved the issue causing the React warning/error about updating a component (`App`) while rendering another component (`SpotifyPrototype`).\n\n### Root Cause\nIn React, functional state updates like `setProgress(prev => { ... })` are executed synchronously by React during the render calculation phase. Inside the progress state updater function, there was a call to `handleNextSong()`, which immediately performed multiple parent and sibling state modifications (including triggering `onTrackAction` to log events in `App` and changing active song IDs). This caused React to warn that side effects and sibling component updates were being triggered synchronously during the rendering cycle.\n\n### Solution Implemented\n- **Isolated Side Effects**: Refactored the progress timer in `SpotifyPrototype.tsx` to purely calculate the track progress (incrementing up to `100` and stopping) without executing side effects inside the state-updater.\n- **Created a Dedicated Synchronization Effect**: Introduced a new, dedicated `useEffect` hook that explicitly monitors `progress` and `isPlaying`. When `progress` reaches or exceeds `100`, it cleanly fires `handleNextSong()` and resets the track bar. This ensures all transitions and telemetry updates execute safely during React\'s commit phase rather than during active render cycles."
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
